# Playwright Guidelines

Our repository is not yet migrated to the monorepo structure.

However, we have already created the "projects" folder, where all the apps and libs will be located.

2 app projects currently hold a space for Playwright tests:

- fz-original: corresponds our "feverzone" project which should be migrated here in the future.
- fz-kiosk: feverzone's kiosk section which should be migrated here in the futre, since it is an independent app.

Both projects are referenced in [angular.json](mdc:angular.json) and both contain a "playwright" folder that follows a folder structure from within very similar to the "src" one in Angular projects.

### Folder structure

Each playwright folder should contain a playwright configuration file named "playwright.app.config.ts".

This file imports the common configurations from [playwright.config.ts](mdc:playwright.config.ts) and adds its custom ones.

At the same level we should find folders with app features or domains of our app project e.g. Feverzone's "box-office" or "reservations".

The "app" folder will contain symbols that can be used globally in the playwright context, for any feature. These can be Angular symbols, e.g. components, services, etc. or TypeScript symbols, e.g. enums or models (meaning types and interfaces), etc.

Each feature folder should follow the same folder structure. Take the app one for instance:

```
playwright/app/
├── fixtures/
│    └── *.fixture.ts
├── mocks/
│    └── *.mock.ts or *.sim.mock.ts
├── models/
│    └── *.model.ts or *.sim.model.ts
├── pages/
│    └── *.page.ts
├── tests/
│    ├── e2e/
│    │    └── *.test.ts
│    ├── ui/
│    │    └── *.test.ts
│    └── network/
│         └── *.test.ts
├── utils/
│    └── *.util.ts
```

The tests folder contains three main subfolders that correspond to the `PlaywrightTestCategory` (check playwright.config.ts) types:

- e2e: end-to-end tests. They should tests at flow. Rather than just landing on a page, navigating to a next one at least.
- ui: user interface tests. They should test routing interfaces, also called pages in a Playwright context.
- network: network-related tests. They should test performance on HTTP requests.

### Typing

As a general rule, we should type as strong as possible, including but not exclusively:

- `const` variables e.g. extended test fixtures and Playwright locators.
- Params in callback functions.

We should not type if we are assigning the value to a `new Class()` or if the type can be trivially inferred.

We should never use `any` since that is not a type.

Also, stop using SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE. In Angular projects this is reserved for injection tokens and besides, it does not bring anything.

### Mocks and models

What in Cypress is understood as fixture here it is understood as a mock.

It is preferred to propduce mocks as TypeScript const variables rather than simple JSON files since by doing the latter we lose the typing and therefore the perspectie on data models.

So it is understood that we need to produce models to type the mocks. They are contained in "models" folders. Some of the model files are suffixed with `*.sim.model.ts` instead of simply `*.model.ts`. This is because they reference models that belong to the "src" folder of the actual Angular app but do not directly import those and do not strictly follow the real model.

For the moment we won't be importing those real models, since our purpose would be to share them accross projects.

That is the reason why we will create simulation models, hence the ".sim". They do not need to be the exact original models, just an approximation that gives us an idea of the data structure.

If we foresee that our mock is going to be dynamic, we should not express it as a mock but as a utility function in a `*.util.ts` file.

### Duplications

As mentioned before, we still do not have the monorepo structure that will enable us to retrieve source code from libraries.

This is the reason why there are some snippets that are repeated between e.g. fz-original and fz-kiosk.

They have been marked with a comment. For example:

```ts
/**
 * Same as in fz-kiosk
 */
```

If we see a comment like that and perform changes on the snippet, we should take care of doing the same change consistently in other instance of the same file (they are named the same way).

Because of this issue, we need to be extremly careful not to import the functionality from another project but from the very same project we are in.

- fz-kiosk project will use the custom path `@fz-kiosk-playwright` contained in [tsconfig.json](mdc:tsconfig.json).
- fz-original project will temporarily use relative paths.

### Utility functions

Some of them will relate to the functionality contained in our app but some others will help us stay D.R.Y. and performant by using Playwright test features.

A good example would be the navigation utililty function:

```ts
// e.g. at `projects/fz-original/playwright/app/utils/navigation.util.ts` [navigation.util.ts](mdc:projects/fz-original/playwright/app/utils/navigation.util.ts)
export async function navigateTo({
  page,
  path,
  params,
  expectedRedirect,
  timeout,
  title,
  waitUntil = 'domcontentloaded',
}: NavigateToParam): Promise<void> {
  const localhost: string | undefined = process.env.BASE_URL;
  if (localhost === undefined) {
    throw new Error('BASE_URL environment variable is not defined');
  }
  const navigationPath: string = path ?? '';
  const pathWithParams = params ? getPathWithQueryParams(navigationPath, params) : navigationPath;
  const url: string = getUrl(pathWithParams);
  await page.goto(url, { waitUntil, timeout });
  if (expectedRedirect !== undefined) {
    await expect(page).toHaveURL(getUrl(expectedRedirect));
  } else if (params) {
    await checkUrlWithParams(page, pathWithParams);
  }
  if (title !== undefined) {
    expect(await page.title()).toBe(title);
  }
}
```

We will always prefer to use this wrapper rather than using Playwright's `page.goto()` directly, since it performs some test expectations inside, depending on the params we introduce in it.

As general rules for utility functions:

- They should never be assigned to `const` variables, since that makes them lose the hoisting.
- If a function takes more than 3 params, we should make all params into an object literal and type that single param wiht a noop object. For example:

```ts
const paramsNoop = {
  partnerId: 0,
  planId: 0,
  placeId: 0,
  cartId: '',
  reservationId: '',
};

export function multipleParamsUtil({
  partnerId,
  planId,
  placeId,
  cartId,
  reservationId,
}: typeof paramsNoop): string {
  [...]

  return expect.any(String);
}
```

### Pages, flows and toolkits

For every test file we create, the first thing we need to do in advance is to abstract/wrap every re-usable functionality in a TypeScript class.

If the class refers to an e2e test, **the class will be a Flow** and if the class refers to a ui test, **the class will be a Page**.

If we need to tests a Movies flow, we will create a class called "MoviesFlow". However, if we are only testing 1 interface and not a sequence of them, we will create a "MoviesPage" class instead. For instance:

```ts
// Created at e.g. `projects/fz-original/playwright/movies/pages/movies.page.ts`
export class MoviesPage {
  static readonly headMeta = 'head meta';
  static readonly hero = 'hero';
  this.#ticketingToolkit = new TicketingToolkit(page);

  constructor(
    readonly page: Page,
    readonly lang: string,
    readonly country: string,
  ) {}

  async addTicketsToCart(): Promise<void> {
    await this.#ticketingToolkit.selectMinTickets();
    await this.#ticketingToolkit.addTicketsToCart();
  }

  getHero(): Locator {
    return this.page.getByTestId(MoviesPage.hero);
  }

  getMetadataList(): Promise<string[]> {
    return this.page.$$eval(MoviesPage.headMeta, (elements: (SVGElement | HTMLElement)[]) =>
      elements.map((element: SVGElement | HTMLElement) => element.outerHTML),
    );
  }

  async goToMovies() {
    await navigateTo({ page: this.page, path: `/movies/${this.lang}/${this.country}` });
  }
}
```

Notice, also in the example, that we have assigned a separate TS class to a private property: `TicketingToolkit` (coming from e.g. [ticketing.toolkit.ts](mdc:projects/fz-original/playwright/app/toolkits/ticketing.toolkit.ts)). That is functionality that could be re-used accross pages and/or flows and that we have decided to encapsulate in its own Ticketing **toolkit** which can not only be used for the movies page but also for any other test encapsultation that needs to handle tickets.

As general rules for the creation of these classes:

- Never use data modifiers (public, protected private).
- Do use private identifiers with hash (#) for [private identifiers](mdc:https:/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Classes/Private_properties).
- Mandatory `constructor(readonly page: Page) {}`.
- `static readonly` for static values e.g. locator ids.
- Respect "@typescript-eslint/member-ordering" from `.eslintrc.json`.
- Locators should be properties and not methods.

### Fixtures

The concept of fixture is not the same as in Cypress.

In Playwright, a `test()` is a built-in fixture. But this fixture can be extended and re-extended, creating an abstraction of our test suite.

For example in Feverzone (or fz-original) we need to be always logged in. That is why first we need to create a login fixture, located at [login.fixture.ts](mdc:projects/fz-original/playwright/app/fixtures/login.fixture.ts) and later on extend from it.

```ts
// `projects/fz-original/playwright/app/fixtures/login.fixture.ts`
import { test as base, Page } from '@playwright/test';

import { LoginFixture, PlaywrightExtendedTest } from '../models/fixture.model';
import { PlaywrightInterception } from '../models/interception.model';
import { LoginPage } from '../pages/login.page';
import { interceptPlaywrightRoutes } from '../utils/interception.util';

export function testWithLoginPageInterceptions(requestInterceptions: PlaywrightInterception[]): PlaywrightExtendedTest<LoginFixture> {
  const interceptionsWithoutDuplicates = requestInterceptions
    .reverse()
    .filter(
      (interception: PlaywrightInterception, index: number, self: PlaywrightInterception[]) =>
        self.findIndex((t: PlaywrightInterception) => t.urlPattern === interception.urlPattern) === index,
    )
    .reverse();

  return base.extend<LoginFixture>({
    loginPage: async ({ page }: { page: Page }, use: (loginPage: LoginPage) => Promise<void>) => {
      const loginPage = new LoginPage(page);
      await interceptPlaywrightRoutes(loginPage.page, interceptionsWithoutDuplicates);
      await use(loginPage);
    },
  });
}
```

So basically, following up on the movies example, our movies fixture would look like this:

```ts
// Created at e.g. `projects/fz-original/playwright/movies/models/fixture.model.ts`
export interface MoviesFixture extends LoginFixture {
  moviesPage: MoviesPage;
}

// Created at e.g. `projects/fz-original/playwright/movies/fixtures/movies.fixture.ts`
export function test(partnerId: number, lang: string, country: string): PlaywrightExtendedTest<MoviesFixture> {
  const permissions: Permission[] = ['go_to_movies'];
  const featureFlags: OptimizelyFeatureKey[] = ['movies_view'];
  const optimizelyInterception: PlaywrightInterception = getOptimizelyInterception(partnerId, featureFlags);
  const interceptions: PlaywrightInterception[] = [
    ...getLoginPageDefaultInterceptions(partnerId),
    getPermissionsInterception(partnerId, permissions),
    optimizelyInterception,
  ];

  return testWithLoginPageInterceptions(interceptions).extend<MoviesFixture>({
    tasksPage: async ({ loginPage }, use) => await use(new MoviesPage(loginPage.page, lang, country)),
  });
}
```

Notice that we would create all models for fixtures of a certain domain in the same `fixture.model.ts` file whereas we would dedicate a single file for the movies fixture itself.

So we would be extending the login fixture which at the same time extends from Playwright built-in fixture.

We should include happy path interceptions in this fixture file.

### Tests

Again, following up on the movies example, this is what the test would look like:

```ts
const partnerId = 7532;
// For English.
const lang = 'en';
// For New Zealand
const country = 'nz';
const test: PlaywrightExtendedTest<MoviesFixture> = moviesTest(partnerId, lang, country);

test.describe('Movies', () => {
  test.beforeEach(async ({ loginPage, moviesPage }: MoviesFixture) => {
    await loginPage.goToLogin();
    await moviesPage.goToMovies();
  });

  test.describe('When...', () => {
    test('should...', async ({ moviesPage }: MoviesFixture) => {
      expect(await moviesPage.getHero()).toContain('Hero Text');
    });
  });
});
```

Notice that navigating to login is a prerequisite so this is not a navigation to be taken into consideration when choosing between e2e and ui tests. On the other hand, the `goToMovies()` navigation does not form an e2e either, since it is considered the navigation to the first UI interface we need to test.

We should include override interceptions in this `*.test.ts` file.

This is the way we should structure our test suite:

- FIRST a global `describe()` block.
- THEN a global `beforeEach()` block.
- THEN a number of local `describe()` blocks.
  - THEN inside each one of them as many `test()` cases as we need.
  - AND before each test case, if need be, a local `beforeEach()`.

Of course, we can take full advantage of Playwright's capabilities by using any other test hooks if convenient.

